WEBVTT

1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.074
Tired of searching for subtitles?
Ray generates them instantly: getray.app

2
00:00:13.013 --> 00:00:15.641
["Nemesis" playing]

3
00:01:46.648 --> 00:01:47.649
[music ends]

4
00:01:52.404 --> 00:01:53.822
[guards speaking Russian]

5
00:01:54.865 --> 00:01:55.908
[Bradley sighs]

6
00:02:02.372 --> 00:02:03.498
[guards speaking Russian]

7
00:02:03.582 --> 00:02:05.751
[lights buzzing]

8
00:02:07.961 --> 00:02:09.003
[sighs]

9
00:02:09.086 --> 00:02:10.797
[guards speaking Russian]

10
00:02:14.635 --> 00:02:15.636
[gasps]

11
00:02:15.719 --> 00:02:17.012
[in English] Please! Please.

12
00:02:17.095 --> 00:02:19.348
Can you turn off the light?
Just for a few hours--

13
00:02:23.727 --> 00:02:25.812
[keyboard keys clacking. mouse clicks]

14
00:02:49.127 --> 00:02:50.337
[printer whirring]

15
00:03:02.683 --> 00:03:05.394
[Yanko] <i>And security is ramping up
in Paris as the city prepares</i>

16
00:03:05.477 --> 00:03:08.313
<i>for the opening ceremony
of the Summer Olympic Games.</i>

17
00:03:08.397 --> 00:03:11.733
<i>Organizers are promising a dazzling
spectacle with plenty of surprises.</i>

18
00:03:11.817 --> 00:03:14.069
<i>and later in the hour.
we're gonna take you behind the scenes</i>

19
00:03:14.152 --> 00:03:15.821
<i>and show you
how some of that magic is made.</i>

20
00:03:15.904 --> 00:03:20.742
<i>And finally. it's day 28 of
Bradley Jackson's detainment in Belarus.</i>

21
00:03:20.826 --> 00:03:22.870
<i>We hope and pray that she will come home--</i>

22
00:03:22.953 --> 00:03:23.954
[switches off TV]

23
00:03:48.061 --> 00:03:50.439
Mm-hmm. I understand. I understand.

24
00:03:51.148 --> 00:03:56.486
But it-it has been a month. and every day
we keep having the exact same conversation

25
00:03:56.570 --> 00:03:58.906
while people are forgetting
what's happening to her.

26
00:03:59.615 --> 00:04:02.075
Yes. No. I-I understand. Thank you.

27
00:04:04.328 --> 00:04:07.080
Well. they still won't designate
Bradley as unlawfully detained.

28
00:04:07.164 --> 00:04:09.374
Not until they have more information.

29
00:04:09.458 --> 00:04:13.587
So. we can just add that to the list
of fucked-up shit we cannot fix.

30
00:04:14.588 --> 00:04:16.380
Did you hear anything that I just said?

31
00:04:16.923 --> 00:04:19.301
What? Yes. C-Come here.
You have to see this.

32
00:04:20.552 --> 00:04:22.513
- Come here. Look. Look. look. look.
- What's that?

33
00:04:22.596 --> 00:04:24.348
Okay. This is the EPA report
on Wolf River.

34
00:04:24.431 --> 00:04:26.058
- the one from 2019. right?
- Mm-hmm.

35
00:04:26.141 --> 00:04:30.896
This is the internal Martel emissions doc
that Bradley sent over.

36
00:04:33.815 --> 00:04:35.234
[Alex] They're nowhere close.

37
00:04:35.317 --> 00:04:37.945
- The EPA numbers are way lower.
- [Chip] Mm-hmm. It's way lower.

38
00:04:38.028 --> 00:04:40.280
And. I mean. I don't wanna sound crazy.

39
00:04:40.364 --> 00:04:42.533
but what if somebody falsified
the EPA report?

40
00:04:42.616 --> 00:04:44.743
And maybe...
maybe Martel paid them to do it.

41
00:04:44.826 --> 00:04:47.621
I don't know. That's sounding
a little bit like a Bro conspiracy theory.

42
00:04:47.704 --> 00:04:48.997
What. you mean the future Senator Hartman?

43
00:04:49.081 --> 00:04:50.541
- Oh. don't say that.
- Okay. look.

44
00:04:50.624 --> 00:04:52.835
- Just "what if" for a second. okay?
- Okay. okay.

45
00:04:53.418 --> 00:04:56.004
Bradley's source works at Martel. okay.
She clearly was onto something

46
00:04:56.088 --> 00:04:57.339
they didn't want her to know about.

47
00:04:57.422 --> 00:05:02.386
If we can somehow prove that there was
a cover-up involving the EPA.

48
00:05:03.262 --> 00:05:04.263
that's front-page news.

49
00:05:04.346 --> 00:05:06.139
And then people start talking
about Bradley again.

50
00:05:06.223 --> 00:05:08.308
That's it. that's it.
So now we just need to find somebody

51
00:05:08.392 --> 00:05:10.060
who knows more about these numbers.

52
00:05:10.143 --> 00:05:11.186
Uh. oh. wait. Bradley.

53
00:05:11.270 --> 00:05:14.147
Didn't she say something
about Cory and the EPA report?

54
00:05:14.690 --> 00:05:16.733
Remember? And that's
why he didn't run the story?

55
00:05:17.317 --> 00:05:20.028
Maybe Cory lied.
Maybe he's just covering his ass.

56
00:05:20.112 --> 00:05:22.030
- Mm-hmm.
- Jesus. Alex.

57
00:05:22.990 --> 00:05:26.326
This means Bradley was right.
About all of it.

58
00:05:30.956 --> 00:05:32.958
- [gate unlocks. opens]
- [gasps]

59
00:05:36.837 --> 00:05:38.505
[people chattering]

60
00:05:43.468 --> 00:05:45.095
You are having trouble sleeping?

61
00:05:45.762 --> 00:05:46.847
Yes.

62
00:05:47.681 --> 00:05:49.099
The light never turns off.

63
00:05:50.350 --> 00:05:51.351
Please.

64
00:05:51.435 --> 00:05:53.812
[officer] Who were you meeting in Minsk?

65
00:05:53.896 --> 00:05:56.023
I ca... I can't.

66
00:05:56.106 --> 00:05:57.941
- [officer] I need a name.
- [sighs]

67
00:05:59.067 --> 00:06:01.778
Please. this person is not a dissident. I...

68
00:06:02.863 --> 00:06:04.156
I'm not a spy.

69
00:06:05.115 --> 00:06:06.366
I'm not a spy.

70
00:06:09.786 --> 00:06:11.371
- [footsteps depart]
- [breathes heavily]

71
00:06:11.455 --> 00:06:13.540
[guards speaking Russian]

72
00:06:13.624 --> 00:06:14.708
[sighs]

73
00:06:14.791 --> 00:06:17.961
[heavy metal music playing]

74
00:06:20.214 --> 00:06:22.257
[grunting]

75
00:06:23.217 --> 00:06:25.761
- [high-pitched tone]
- [groaning]

76
00:06:25.844 --> 00:06:27.137
[music stops]

77
00:06:31.058 --> 00:06:33.268
- [Cory. in English] Ah. shit.
- [crew member] That's a cut!

78
00:06:33.352 --> 00:06:35.229
- [buzzer sounds]
- [people chattering]

79
00:06:35.312 --> 00:06:38.190
Goddamn it. Eric?
How long is it gonna take to fix this?

80
00:06:38.273 --> 00:06:39.441
[Eric] Uh. give us a minute.

81
00:06:40.234 --> 00:06:41.944
- [sighs]
- It's like <i>The Matrix</i>. Wow.

82
00:06:42.027 --> 00:06:44.571
Yeah. And I'm dodging
twice as many bullets.

83
00:06:44.655 --> 00:06:45.989
Well. at least you're back up and running.

84
00:06:46.073 --> 00:06:48.283
How are things going with the. uh.
fancy new star?

85
00:06:48.367 --> 00:06:50.577
Hey. how about you just ask me
what you came here to ask me.

86
00:06:50.661 --> 00:06:53.705
- 'cause I'm a little busy right now.
- Hmm. Not in the mood for foreplay. huh?

87
00:06:53.789 --> 00:06:56.959
Well. life is short and I love you.
but I'm not in love with you.

88
00:06:57.042 --> 00:06:58.043
Okay.

89
00:06:58.126 --> 00:06:59.837
So I have been sifting
through the information

90
00:06:59.920 --> 00:07:02.047
that Bradley sent over
before she was detained.

91
00:07:02.130 --> 00:07:04.049
It's paperwork from Martel Chemical.

92
00:07:04.132 --> 00:07:07.928
Soil reports. groundwater tests.
and there's something weird.

93
00:07:08.011 --> 00:07:12.349
The internal numbers of Martel don't match
the EPA report on Wolf River.

94
00:07:13.058 --> 00:07:14.351
You know anything about this?

95
00:07:15.519 --> 00:07:17.396
No. I don't.

96
00:07:18.522 --> 00:07:20.482
Really? You're-You're totally in the dark?

97
00:07:20.566 --> 00:07:22.317
As I explained to Bradley.

98
00:07:23.193 --> 00:07:28.073
legal told me to move on
from the story in 2019. so I did.

99
00:07:28.156 --> 00:07:31.243
I turned that page in my life.
and I'm not trying to go back.

100
00:07:31.326 --> 00:07:32.452
- Okay. I get it--
- All right.

101
00:07:32.536 --> 00:07:36.290
But even if it means
we could bring Bradley back home?

102
00:07:36.373 --> 00:07:38.959
The only people
that can help Bradley right now

103
00:07:39.042 --> 00:07:40.711
are the fine folks
at the State Department.

104
00:07:40.794 --> 00:07:43.088
I agree. And if we break Bradley's story.

105
00:07:43.172 --> 00:07:45.382
then it'll put pressure on them
to get on it. right?

106
00:07:45.465 --> 00:07:47.467
Yeah. well. that's certainly a theory.

107
00:07:49.219 --> 00:07:50.637
Well... [scoffs] Come on. man.

108
00:07:50.721 --> 00:07:53.473
Like. I don't really know what's going on
between Bradley and the feds.

109
00:07:53.557 --> 00:07:56.852
but they're clearly not bending over
backwards to help her right now.

110
00:07:56.935 --> 00:08:00.480
Well. yeah. I mean. karma sucks.
doesn't it. Chip?

111
00:08:01.815 --> 00:08:02.900
What is wrong with you?

112
00:08:03.483 --> 00:08:04.484
Come again?

113
00:08:05.277 --> 00:08:06.653
She's in a fucking gulag. man.

114
00:08:06.737 --> 00:08:08.655
I understand you're mad at her
or something. but like--

115
00:08:08.739 --> 00:08:09.740
Mad?

116
00:08:09.823 --> 00:08:12.993
As I'm sure you know.
she strip-mined my phone.

117
00:08:13.076 --> 00:08:17.372
and. I don't know. my fucking soul
on all things Wolf River.

118
00:08:17.456 --> 00:08:20.417
Perfect timing. by the way. It really
set me up for the last couple of weeks.

119
00:08:20.501 --> 00:08:23.545
I don't know if you've ever had
the honor of picking out an urn

120
00:08:23.629 --> 00:08:25.547
for the pile of dust
formerly called your mother.

121
00:08:25.631 --> 00:08:28.550
There's so many choices.
They got rosewood. they got ceramic.

122
00:08:28.634 --> 00:08:30.552
they got biodegradable. they got engraved.

123
00:08:30.636 --> 00:08:33.847
It is fantastic how we've managed
to incorporate death

124
00:08:33.931 --> 00:08:36.433
into the consumer economy.
While we're on the subject.

125
00:08:36.517 --> 00:08:38.434
quick question.
what do you think is worse?

126
00:08:39.144 --> 00:08:42.438
Pretending to love someone
so you can fuck 'em over.

127
00:08:42.523 --> 00:08:45.234
or killing yourself in front of them?

128
00:08:46.360 --> 00:08:48.237
It's... you know... I just...

129
00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:49.321
[groans]

130
00:08:51.281 --> 00:08:52.324
Okay. I'm gonna go.

131
00:08:52.407 --> 00:08:54.576
Well. that's the best idea
you had all day.

132
00:08:55.369 --> 00:08:57.079
Copy of the EPA report on Wolf River.

133
00:08:57.162 --> 00:08:58.747
- [sighs]
- Maybe it'll jog your memory.

134
00:09:07.047 --> 00:09:08.674
And for what it's worth. man.

135
00:09:09.383 --> 00:09:12.511
Bradley was genuinely torn up
about what happened between you two.

136
00:09:14.221 --> 00:09:15.973
I-I think it really got to her.

137
00:09:17.558 --> 00:09:18.684
I'm sorry for your loss.

138
00:09:23.981 --> 00:09:27.234
[heavy metal music playing]

139
00:09:30.362 --> 00:09:31.655
[music stops]

140
00:09:35.784 --> 00:09:36.785
[sighs]

141
00:09:37.578 --> 00:09:38.704
[gasping]

142
00:09:42.165 --> 00:09:44.001
[door opens]

143
00:09:46.879 --> 00:09:49.339
[Bradley groaning]

144
00:09:49.423 --> 00:09:50.424
[winces]

145
00:09:51.466 --> 00:09:52.718
[whimpers]

146
00:09:56.597 --> 00:09:58.807
- You don't look well.
- [whispering] No.

147
00:10:00.267 --> 00:10:01.935
[officer] Are you ready to sleep?

148
00:10:02.811 --> 00:10:05.314
Yes. [sighing]

149
00:10:09.109 --> 00:10:10.110
[sighs]

150
00:10:10.194 --> 00:10:12.654
The name. then sleep.

151
00:10:15.240 --> 00:10:17.576
We just want to talk to them.

152
00:10:18.285 --> 00:10:19.369
That's all.

153
00:10:24.166 --> 00:10:26.210
[people shouting]

154
00:10:33.383 --> 00:10:35.886
[pencil scratching]

155
00:10:42.184 --> 00:10:43.268
[Bradley groans]

156
00:10:52.319 --> 00:10:53.487
[speaks Russian]

157
00:10:55.489 --> 00:10:57.282
- [speaks Russian]
- [groans]

158
00:11:04.498 --> 00:11:06.416
[door closes]

159
00:11:06.500 --> 00:11:08.001
[heavy metal music resumes]

160
00:11:15.008 --> 00:11:16.009
[music stops]

161
00:11:18.929 --> 00:11:20.347
[Cory. in English] <i>Why did you come back?</i>

162
00:11:22.850 --> 00:11:24.101
For you. obviously.

163
00:11:24.184 --> 00:11:27.729
Mm-hmm. Well. yeah. I get that.
I'm totally irresistible.

164
00:11:29.439 --> 00:11:30.941
Why did I come back?

165
00:11:32.234 --> 00:11:33.443
I don't know.

166
00:11:34.319 --> 00:11:35.737
I mean. if I'm being honest.

167
00:11:36.363 --> 00:11:38.532
it was a little bit boring
teaching journalism.

168
00:11:38.615 --> 00:11:39.616
[chuckles]

169
00:11:40.993 --> 00:11:44.371
Also. I figured if nobody was gonna
punish me for what I did.

170
00:11:45.873 --> 00:11:47.332
guess I could punish myself.

171
00:11:52.337 --> 00:11:54.798
Maybe it's time to stop being punished.

172
00:11:55.632 --> 00:11:57.301
Maybe there's been enough of that.

173
00:12:02.431 --> 00:12:04.266
[whispering] You know
what I keep thinking about?

174
00:12:04.349 --> 00:12:05.475
Hmm?

175
00:12:07.811 --> 00:12:09.396
The night you told me you loved me.

176
00:12:09.479 --> 00:12:11.190
[Cory inhales deeply] Hmm.

177
00:12:12.441 --> 00:12:15.194
Even when your brother was missing
and you thought he might be dead?

178
00:12:15.277 --> 00:12:17.237
Well. see.
that's what's so great about you.

179
00:12:17.321 --> 00:12:19.698
is you have impeccable sense of timing.

180
00:12:20.449 --> 00:12:22.743
Well. it's only been four years.

181
00:12:22.826 --> 00:12:25.204
You feel like you're ready
to get back to me on that?

182
00:12:28.540 --> 00:12:30.375
You scared the shit out of me that night.

183
00:12:33.003 --> 00:12:35.297
Then how did we end up here?

184
00:12:39.343 --> 00:12:41.720
Maybe I just wanted to figure out
what I was so scared of.

185
00:12:45.224 --> 00:12:46.850
[breathing deeply]

186
00:12:48.018 --> 00:12:49.186
Any answers?

187
00:12:50.521 --> 00:12:51.563
I don't know.

188
00:12:53.273 --> 00:12:54.399
It's like.

189
00:12:56.193 --> 00:12:57.444
there's you.

190
00:12:58.862 --> 00:13:00.531
and then there's everybody else.

191
00:13:03.158 --> 00:13:04.535
But there's you.

192
00:13:07.454 --> 00:13:09.248
- [sighs]
- And you're always with me.

193
00:13:11.166 --> 00:13:12.876
Even when I don't want you to be.

194
00:13:14.962 --> 00:13:16.088
You got in.

195
00:13:18.757 --> 00:13:20.300
I don't know how you did it.

196
00:13:21.885 --> 00:13:23.053
But you did.

197
00:13:33.730 --> 00:13:35.023
So...

198
00:13:38.902 --> 00:13:40.279
are we gonna try this?

199
00:13:40.863 --> 00:13:41.947
[sighs]

200
00:13:44.867 --> 00:13:46.785
[whispering]
I'm gonna fuck it up a little.

201
00:13:46.869 --> 00:13:47.870
[whispering] Me too.

202
00:13:49.454 --> 00:13:50.455
[sighs]

203
00:13:50.956 --> 00:13:53.000
Well. as long as it's not just me.

204
00:13:55.419 --> 00:13:59.882
I will do my very best to disappoint you.

205
00:14:01.758 --> 00:14:02.801
Good.

206
00:14:10.642 --> 00:14:11.643
Mmm.

207
00:14:27.784 --> 00:14:29.203
[Ben] Oh. hey.

208
00:14:29.286 --> 00:14:31.163
- Hey.
- You're here late.

209
00:14:31.747 --> 00:14:34.124
You know me.
The Games are around the corner. So...

210
00:14:34.208 --> 00:14:38.670
Hmm. Actually. I was looking for Layla.
but maybe you can help me?

211
00:14:39.755 --> 00:14:42.090
After the whole Stella O24. uh...

212
00:14:42.174 --> 00:14:43.300
Nuclear meltdown?

213
00:14:43.383 --> 00:14:46.386
Well. I was gonna say. "situation."

214
00:14:46.470 --> 00:14:48.180
- but yeah. sure.
- Oh. Okay.

215
00:14:48.263 --> 00:14:51.225
Um. we've been triple-checking
the few AI elements

216
00:14:51.308 --> 00:14:52.893
that we're gonna roll out in Paris.

217
00:14:52.976 --> 00:14:56.813
In case Yanko's avatar starts talking
about how his radicalized ex-girlfriend

218
00:14:56.897 --> 00:14:58.649
got dragged out of the building
by the FBI?

219
00:14:58.732 --> 00:15:00.817
It's. uh... It's funny
you should mention that.

220
00:15:00.901 --> 00:15:05.155
So. IT flagged something in their report.

221
00:15:05.239 --> 00:15:09.993
It looks like there was some unauthorized
access of the Alex language model

222
00:15:10.077 --> 00:15:11.620
from a <i>TMS</i> computer.

223
00:15:11.703 --> 00:15:15.999
This happened a couple of months ago.
Uh. before you left. In May.

224
00:15:16.834 --> 00:15:19.378
Do you mind taking a look at it for me?
I'm kinda buried.

225
00:15:19.461 --> 00:15:21.213
<i>TMS</i> is not my problem anymore.

226
00:15:21.296 --> 00:15:24.675
Well. it happened on your watch. so...

227
00:15:25.968 --> 00:15:27.594
I'd really appreciate it.

228
00:15:30.138 --> 00:15:31.431
Yeah. Sure.

229
00:15:31.515 --> 00:15:32.850
Thank you.

230
00:15:33.559 --> 00:15:34.643
You're welcome.

231
00:15:37.521 --> 00:15:38.689
[sighs]

232
00:15:41.900 --> 00:15:42.985
[exhales sharply]

233
00:15:43.068 --> 00:15:45.070
["Where's the Catch?" playing]

234
00:16:08.719 --> 00:16:10.137
[sighs]

235
00:16:15.976 --> 00:16:17.686
[song continues]

236
00:16:52.095 --> 00:16:53.514
[song continues]

237
00:17:00.854 --> 00:17:01.855
[song fades out]

238
00:17:03.023 --> 00:17:06.276
Do you remember anyone working
on AI projects for <i>TMS</i> back in May?

239
00:17:06.359 --> 00:17:09.320
Somebody who would have had access
to Alex's avatar?

240
00:17:09.404 --> 00:17:11.448
Uh. not really.
and why would anyone do that?

241
00:17:11.531 --> 00:17:13.867
Yeah. I thought
all the AI stuff was Ben's team?

242
00:17:13.951 --> 00:17:16.286
<i>TMS</i> is very hands-off on that.

243
00:17:16.369 --> 00:17:19.373
- Right? Yeah. Uh...
- Right. Yeah. Thanks.

244
00:18:51.924 --> 00:18:53.050
Cory?

245
00:18:58.138 --> 00:18:59.223
[sighs]

246
00:19:03.310 --> 00:19:04.353
What is it?

247
00:19:08.315 --> 00:19:09.399
What's wrong?

248
00:19:12.611 --> 00:19:13.612
[sighs]

249
00:19:23.830 --> 00:19:26.250
Did you have something to do
with Bradley getting taken?

250
00:19:28.877 --> 00:19:31.880
- Cory...
- Hey. just tell me.

251
00:19:31.964 --> 00:19:33.632
Of course not.

252
00:19:35.133 --> 00:19:36.510
Why would you think that?

253
00:19:36.593 --> 00:19:39.388
Well. your family must have
a financial interest in Martel

254
00:19:39.471 --> 00:19:42.599
since you paid Fred to bury the story.

255
00:19:42.683 --> 00:19:44.393
I thought we'd put this behind us.

256
00:19:44.476 --> 00:19:46.520
Yeah. we did. but Bradley brought it back.

257
00:19:49.022 --> 00:19:50.899
She was getting close.

258
00:19:52.651 --> 00:19:54.236
She was getting close to something.

259
00:19:55.028 --> 00:19:57.656
and now not even the Red Cross
can get in to see her.

260
00:20:00.200 --> 00:20:03.036
And you think
I had something to do with that?

261
00:20:03.537 --> 00:20:05.873
I don't know what to think.

262
00:20:07.833 --> 00:20:09.084
[sighs]

263
00:20:12.379 --> 00:20:13.797
No one knew she was going.

264
00:20:15.591 --> 00:20:18.427
Ask Alex. Ask anyone.

265
00:20:18.510 --> 00:20:22.431
I think your family can help get her out.
And I think I can help your family.

266
00:20:23.807 --> 00:20:29.021
Chip is looking into all of this.
and he's circling around the EPA report.

267
00:20:29.104 --> 00:20:31.398
But he doesn't know
that I have the real one.

268
00:20:32.983 --> 00:20:36.737
The one that proves that Martel is liable

269
00:20:36.820 --> 00:20:39.239
for all the things they did
to those people.

270
00:20:41.700 --> 00:20:46.246
And once Bradley is back.
you and your family can have the report.

271
00:20:49.708 --> 00:20:51.168
An insurance policy.

272
00:20:51.919 --> 00:20:53.712
Do whatever the fuck you want with it.

273
00:20:54.922 --> 00:20:58.258
[scoffs] My family.
they can't wave a magic wand.

274
00:20:58.342 --> 00:21:00.010
They can do something.

275
00:21:04.431 --> 00:21:06.225
[sighs] Maybe.

276
00:21:10.854 --> 00:21:11.980
I'll call them.

277
00:21:13.774 --> 00:21:14.775
For you.

278
00:21:20.239 --> 00:21:21.281
Cory...

279
00:21:22.574 --> 00:21:23.784
[sighs]

280
00:21:27.704 --> 00:21:29.289
I know you feel alone.

281
00:21:30.415 --> 00:21:31.542
But I'm here.

282
00:21:32.668 --> 00:21:33.794
I'm with you.

283
00:21:40.676 --> 00:21:41.927
Come back to bed.

284
00:21:43.637 --> 00:21:44.680
All right?

285
00:21:57.234 --> 00:21:58.235
Hello?

286
00:22:05.617 --> 00:22:06.869
Bart.

287
00:22:06.952 --> 00:22:08.203
What are you doing here?

288
00:22:12.416 --> 00:22:13.834
Deepfake of Alex?

289
00:22:15.794 --> 00:22:19.047
You were there when the Iranians defected.
producing the segment.

290
00:22:20.757 --> 00:22:23.135
Then you accessed the AI software.

291
00:22:24.303 --> 00:22:25.304
Why?

292
00:22:27.890 --> 00:22:29.433
Who told you to do that?

293
00:22:32.477 --> 00:22:36.023
Tell me what you know
and I'll keep your name out of it.

294
00:22:39.276 --> 00:22:40.736
[phone buzzing]

295
00:22:45.324 --> 00:22:46.408
[sighs]

296
00:22:49.745 --> 00:22:50.746
Mia...

297
00:23:07.513 --> 00:23:09.348
[assistant] Ms... Uh. Ms. Levy?

298
00:23:11.433 --> 00:23:14.102
You lied to me. You fucking lied.

299
00:23:14.686 --> 00:23:17.022
The Iranians did not create that deepfake.

300
00:23:17.105 --> 00:23:18.190
You did.

301
00:23:18.273 --> 00:23:21.777
[shouting] Do you know how much
that fucked me up?

302
00:23:22.402 --> 00:23:25.155
You stole my voice. You used me.

303
00:23:25.239 --> 00:23:26.490
I don't even know
what you're talking about.

304
00:23:26.573 --> 00:23:30.244
You were going to use that video
to get me fired.

305
00:23:30.327 --> 00:23:31.912
and the only reason you didn't

306
00:23:31.995 --> 00:23:35.541
is because things got complicated
with Zeke and those protesters.

307
00:23:36.542 --> 00:23:37.793
My God. I'm starting to question

308
00:23:37.876 --> 00:23:40.921
every single thing you have done
since you got here.

309
00:23:41.004 --> 00:23:44.341
Preach sisterhood
and then you edge all of us out.

310
00:23:44.967 --> 00:23:47.052
Laura. me. Stella...

311
00:23:47.135 --> 00:23:50.305
Oh. Oh. so now you're blaming me
for her fuck-up too.

312
00:23:50.931 --> 00:23:53.517
I expect your resignation
by the end of today.

313
00:23:54.852 --> 00:23:57.938
Otherwise. I go to the board
and <i>The New York Times</i>.

314
00:24:00.816 --> 00:24:01.942
I'm sorry.

315
00:24:03.402 --> 00:24:06.113
I'm not resigning. You are.

316
00:24:07.990 --> 00:24:09.783
And why would I do that?

317
00:24:09.867 --> 00:24:12.870
Do you know how many laws you broke
when you went to the opera?

318
00:24:14.037 --> 00:24:17.916
You did business with a Russian oligarch
sanctioned by the US government.

319
00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:20.836
The FCC could shut us down
for a stunt like that.

320
00:24:20.919 --> 00:24:22.963
As an executive at this company.

321
00:24:23.714 --> 00:24:27.259
you acted against the well-being
of UBN and its shareholders.

322
00:24:29.261 --> 00:24:31.180
You have 24 hours to step down.

323
00:24:32.764 --> 00:24:34.641
[tense music playing]

324
00:24:59.875 --> 00:25:01.001
[music fades]

325
00:25:01.084 --> 00:25:02.336
[Alex] She knows.

326
00:25:02.419 --> 00:25:06.632
Ivanov. the trade we were trying to make. everything.

327
00:25:06.715 --> 00:25:09.676
I should have never reached out to him.
I knew this could blow back on us.

328
00:25:09.760 --> 00:25:11.178
How the fuck did she find out?

329
00:25:11.261 --> 00:25:12.888
I don't know. I don't know.

330
00:25:12.971 --> 00:25:17.017
She just told me that I have 24 hours
to resign or-or she's gonna call the feds.

331
00:25:18.060 --> 00:25:19.728
- Alex. that cannot happen.
- [sighs]

332
00:25:19.811 --> 00:25:22.856
- Nobody can find out about this.
- I know that. I know.

333
00:25:22.940 --> 00:25:24.942
[sighs. stammers] Bradley.
What about Bradley?

334
00:25:25.901 --> 00:25:28.403
State Department already
dragging its feet.

335
00:25:29.112 --> 00:25:33.825
Celine. she knew something like this
would completely compromise her case.

336
00:25:33.909 --> 00:25:35.452
Bradley fucking Jackson.

337
00:25:36.119 --> 00:25:38.580
My God. Stuck in a fucking gulag
in Eastern Europe

338
00:25:38.664 --> 00:25:40.332
and she's still a human wrecking ball.

339
00:25:40.415 --> 00:25:43.585
I just can't... can't believe
this 22 years. this is how it ends.

340
00:25:43.669 --> 00:25:46.171
[inhales sharply] I worked
so fucking hard for that place.

341
00:25:46.255 --> 00:25:48.382
Hey. hey. hey. hey. Listen to me.

342
00:25:49.007 --> 00:25:51.134
- [sighs]
- You stopped me.

343
00:25:52.135 --> 00:25:54.054
All right. I'm pretty sure
you can shut her down.

344
00:25:54.137 --> 00:25:56.431
Now. if she knows
about some off-book trade.

345
00:25:56.515 --> 00:25:59.893
then she's doing some backroom deals
of her own. which makes her vulnerable.

346
00:25:59.977 --> 00:26:01.937
- You're right.
- So dig.

347
00:26:02.020 --> 00:26:05.190
Find out where the bodies are buried.
Who knows her secrets?

348
00:26:06.733 --> 00:26:08.068
["Undedicated" playing on speakers]

349
00:26:08.151 --> 00:26:09.653
[knock on door]

350
00:26:15.409 --> 00:26:16.577
- Hi.
- Oh. hi.

351
00:26:16.660 --> 00:26:19.454
So sorry to drop in like this.
I know you have so much going on.

352
00:26:19.538 --> 00:26:22.374
- Um. it's actually not a good time.
- I'm sorry. But I can't wait. honestly.

353
00:26:22.457 --> 00:26:26.503
She wants me out.
Celine is forcing me out.

354
00:26:26.587 --> 00:26:29.464
I'm supposed to... to resign.
I'm supposed to step aside

355
00:26:29.548 --> 00:26:31.925
- like it's my fucking idea...
- Hey. can we talk about this tomorrow?

356
00:26:32.009 --> 00:26:33.260
...and I'm not gonna fucking do that.

357
00:26:33.343 --> 00:26:35.304
I know this has everything
to do with Bradley.

358
00:26:35.387 --> 00:26:37.931
I can't prove it. but I know it.

359
00:26:38.015 --> 00:26:42.728
And Cory. I know that you know her well.
so just give me some... some dirt on her.

360
00:26:42.811 --> 00:26:45.397
- Come on. You traffic in this shit.
- [chuckles]

361
00:26:45.480 --> 00:26:47.274
I don't care what it is. Insider trading.

362
00:26:47.357 --> 00:26:49.484
- Tax evasion. I don't care.
- [sighs. groans]

363
00:26:49.568 --> 00:26:51.278
- I just need something.
- [door opens]

364
00:26:51.361 --> 00:26:53.405
- [Celine] Sorry I'm late.
- [keys jingle]

365
00:26:53.488 --> 00:26:54.698
[door closes]

366
00:26:56.575 --> 00:26:58.952
[sighs] I had...

367
00:27:01.038 --> 00:27:02.080
Oh.

368
00:27:03.790 --> 00:27:05.709
[song continues]

369
00:27:12.257 --> 00:27:14.092
Okay. Of course.

370
00:27:16.512 --> 00:27:18.639
I mean. just... [sighs]

371
00:27:20.641 --> 00:27:21.934
Why wouldn't you?

372
00:27:24.728 --> 00:27:25.812
[slams door]

373
00:27:32.402 --> 00:27:33.445
[song stops]

374
00:27:36.031 --> 00:27:41.662
[Yanko] Alex. you have been the heart
and soul of this network now for so long.

375
00:27:41.745 --> 00:27:44.164
How does it feel to-to be saying goodbye?

376
00:27:44.248 --> 00:27:47.334
{\an8}It honestly... uh. bittersweet.

377
00:27:47.417 --> 00:27:52.130
{\an8}You know. this place has been my. uh...
my home. You guys are my family.

378
00:27:52.214 --> 00:27:55.968
{\an8}Heck. I know. Well. we feel the same way.
We just... I mean. this is so sudden.

379
00:27:56.051 --> 00:27:58.178
{\an8}Honestly. I just can't
quite believe it's happening at all.

380
00:27:58.262 --> 00:28:01.807
{\an8}Yeah. I know. Well. it's...
it's something that I've been. you know.

381
00:28:01.890 --> 00:28:04.977
{\an8}I've been thinking about for a while. so...

382
00:28:05.602 --> 00:28:06.854
Well. we're gonna miss you in Paris.

383
00:28:06.937 --> 00:28:09.106
- That's for sure. right?
- Mmm.

384
00:28:09.189 --> 00:28:14.152
Can you talk about your decision?
What brought you to this moment?

385
00:28:15.112 --> 00:28:17.614
[Alex] Well... [sighs] ...two years ago.

386
00:28:17.698 --> 00:28:21.785
I think we felt the company
needed to change.

387
00:28:21.869 --> 00:28:26.915
so I stayed through the merger
to help make UBN a place

388
00:28:26.999 --> 00:28:29.585
that we could be proud of. where...

389
00:28:32.880 --> 00:28:36.258
there's real transparency.

390
00:28:36.341 --> 00:28:37.342
Real trust.

391
00:28:38.218 --> 00:28:39.928
And you feel we've achieved that.

392
00:28:44.016 --> 00:28:46.894
I do. Yes. I do.

393
00:28:48.228 --> 00:28:51.857
And you know my... [clears throat]
...my best memories of this place.

394
00:28:51.940 --> 00:28:53.942
it's not ju... you know.
not just the fun times we had

395
00:28:54.026 --> 00:28:55.152
'cause we would have a lot of fun.

396
00:28:55.235 --> 00:28:59.323
but it's also the storms
that we weathered together. you know.

397
00:28:59.406 --> 00:29:02.659
And. um... Yeah. everybody said
that we would never make it.

398
00:29:03.744 --> 00:29:10.209
that legacy media was dead.
and real journalism doesn't matter.

399
00:29:11.710 --> 00:29:17.466
But it really does matter. right?
It matters more than ever.

400
00:29:17.549 --> 00:29:20.385
[Yanko] Well. you've absolutely been our...
our resident truth-teller.

401
00:29:20.469 --> 00:29:23.263
I mean. it's <i>Unfiltered</i>. you know.
Right there in the title of it.

402
00:29:41.949 --> 00:29:43.075
Miles.

403
00:29:44.409 --> 00:29:45.410
Celine.

404
00:29:50.541 --> 00:29:51.917
Why are you here?

405
00:29:53.085 --> 00:29:54.378
You haven't called.

406
00:29:55.337 --> 00:29:56.839
This is my home.

407
00:29:57.631 --> 00:30:00.008
- I live here.
- Well. not recently.

408
00:30:00.551 --> 00:30:01.718
I needed time to think.

409
00:30:01.802 --> 00:30:02.803
Oh.

410
00:30:03.470 --> 00:30:05.973
And what great revelation
did you have out there in the woods?

411
00:30:06.056 --> 00:30:08.725
That I wanted to come back.

412
00:30:09.685 --> 00:30:11.144
figure things out.

413
00:30:12.062 --> 00:30:14.982
But then. I found this.

414
00:30:17.025 --> 00:30:18.318
[scoffs]

415
00:30:18.402 --> 00:30:21.905
You were there at the studio without me.

416
00:30:21.989 --> 00:30:23.156
[chuckles]

417
00:30:24.741 --> 00:30:27.035
Please. Miles. After what you did--

418
00:30:27.119 --> 00:30:28.412
Who were you with?

419
00:30:28.495 --> 00:30:30.998
Do you understand I wasn't sure
I'd ever see you again?

420
00:30:31.081 --> 00:30:33.625
Celine. who was it?

421
00:30:34.293 --> 00:30:35.544
[sighs]

422
00:30:37.588 --> 00:30:39.590
[phone buzzing]

423
00:30:45.929 --> 00:30:48.515
- Yep.
- [doorman] <i>Ms. Levy. your father is here.</i>

424
00:30:50.601 --> 00:30:52.144
[sighs]

425
00:30:52.227 --> 00:30:53.520
Send him up.

426
00:30:56.648 --> 00:30:58.150
Dad.

427
00:30:58.233 --> 00:31:00.319
I've just had such a long day.

428
00:31:00.402 --> 00:31:02.446
Don't worry. I won't stay long.

429
00:31:02.529 --> 00:31:06.366
I realize that
after our last brief encounter.

430
00:31:07.201 --> 00:31:09.453
I'm not the most welcome person here.

431
00:31:10.037 --> 00:31:13.040
I just don't have it in me for
another round of all of that. you know.

432
00:31:13.123 --> 00:31:16.752
No. no. no. None of that. I think
we both said all we needed to say.

433
00:31:17.419 --> 00:31:19.171
No. it was just that I...

434
00:31:20.797 --> 00:31:22.508
Well. I saw your show today.

435
00:31:24.301 --> 00:31:25.552
[sighs]

436
00:31:25.636 --> 00:31:28.931
Quite sudden. your decision to step away.

437
00:31:29.431 --> 00:31:33.101
It's funny that all of a sudden
now you take interest in my career.

438
00:31:33.769 --> 00:31:35.812
The day that it's over. [chuckles]

439
00:31:37.105 --> 00:31:38.357
[chuckles]

440
00:31:40.484 --> 00:31:43.445
Is this about losing the Biden interview?

441
00:31:44.196 --> 00:31:46.073
[sighs] You know. no. It's just...

442
00:31:47.491 --> 00:31:49.117
It's just... it was time.

443
00:31:49.201 --> 00:31:50.536
I saw you at work.

444
00:31:51.036 --> 00:31:55.165
You were in your element.
utterly engaged with the task at hand.

445
00:31:55.249 --> 00:31:56.875
[inhales deeply]

446
00:31:56.959 --> 00:31:59.920
You didn't look like someone
with one foot out of the door.

447
00:32:00.712 --> 00:32:04.800
Heck. you reminded me of me
when I was your age.

448
00:32:06.718 --> 00:32:10.430
Your performance today might have
fooled America.

449
00:32:10.514 --> 00:32:12.683
But remember. I've been about a bit.

450
00:32:12.766 --> 00:32:15.853
I know the hallmarks
of a forced confession.

451
00:32:20.899 --> 00:32:22.734
Do you want to talk to me about it?

452
00:32:25.445 --> 00:32:27.072
It's such a long story.

453
00:32:27.781 --> 00:32:32.119
Well. that's the beauty
of a public disgrace.

454
00:32:33.829 --> 00:32:36.290
Suddenly all you have is time.

455
00:32:37.249 --> 00:32:39.001
Yeah. we gotta move
the production meeting up 'cause the...

456
00:32:39.084 --> 00:32:42.171
- [banging on door]
- What the... Fuck me. I'll call you back.

457
00:32:46.258 --> 00:32:48.302
- We need to talk.
- Oh. Miles. hi.

458
00:32:48.385 --> 00:32:50.637
Well. yeah. [sighs]

459
00:32:50.721 --> 00:32:51.972
Come on in.

460
00:32:52.806 --> 00:32:55.934
Hey. Cory.
I should throw you out a fucking window!

461
00:32:56.018 --> 00:32:57.186
Oh. please don't.

462
00:32:58.145 --> 00:32:59.521
What do you want with my wife?

463
00:32:59.605 --> 00:33:01.190
Ah. you know. we've got
a business arrangement.

464
00:33:01.273 --> 00:33:03.358
Oh. is that what you're calling it?

465
00:33:03.442 --> 00:33:06.695
Your late-night coke binge
with a little fucking on the side.

466
00:33:06.778 --> 00:33:09.156
Oh. we have been
helping each other out a little bit.

467
00:33:09.239 --> 00:33:10.574
You sure as shit haven't been around.

468
00:33:10.657 --> 00:33:12.034
- How's Stella?
- Fuck you.

469
00:33:12.117 --> 00:33:14.286
You think she's on your side?
You think she's got your back?

470
00:33:14.369 --> 00:33:16.413
Like I said. we have an arrangement.

471
00:33:16.496 --> 00:33:19.208
Oh. You have no idea. do you?
You can't see it.

472
00:33:19.291 --> 00:33:21.251
You're the fall guy. Cory.

473
00:33:21.793 --> 00:33:24.338
You always have been
ever since she made you Head of News.

474
00:33:24.421 --> 00:33:26.924
Buddy. you're talking about Wolf River?
I already know about this.

475
00:33:27.007 --> 00:33:28.842
And I should've known that
you knew about it too.

476
00:33:28.926 --> 00:33:30.802
You have no idea what you were part of.

477
00:33:30.886 --> 00:33:33.931
I think I do. I read the real EPA report.

478
00:33:34.014 --> 00:33:36.475
Parting gift from my mother. Remember her?

479
00:33:36.558 --> 00:33:38.519
She figured out that
Celine was gonna bury it.

480
00:33:38.602 --> 00:33:40.479
so she left me a copy.

481
00:33:40.562 --> 00:33:42.898
My own little get-out-of-jail-free card.

482
00:33:42.981 --> 00:33:46.235
Oh. you think...
you think Martha was a whistleblower?

483
00:33:47.069 --> 00:33:48.487
Oh. Cory.

484
00:33:48.987 --> 00:33:50.739
No. no. She was part of it.

485
00:33:51.615 --> 00:33:53.242
She brokered the deal with Celine.

486
00:33:53.325 --> 00:33:55.202
Miles. you don't know
what the fuck you're talking about.

487
00:33:55.285 --> 00:33:59.248
No. no. Yes. yes.
Your mom buried the original report.

488
00:33:59.915 --> 00:34:02.626
And she had some friends over
at the EPA and she gave them a call.

489
00:34:02.709 --> 00:34:05.128
And she paid them to doctor the numbers.

490
00:34:05.212 --> 00:34:06.922
Now why the fuck would she do that?

491
00:34:07.005 --> 00:34:08.297
For you.

492
00:34:08.382 --> 00:34:11.009
Because you were spiraling in LA.

493
00:34:11.092 --> 00:34:13.469
and Celine went to her
and promised to get you out

494
